cified)", "c": null, "w": "104450"}]}], "works_created": [], "quotes": [], "about_quotes": [{"speaker": "William Randolph \"Cozy\" Cole", "relation": "played with", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "It was Jack Teagarden, Earl Hines were heading the group, was Peanuts Hucko; Max Kaminsky; Jack Lesberg and me.", "doc_title": "53342_Cozy Cole oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/53342/"}, {"speaker": "George Wein", "relation": "played with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "And then one time they had a band coming to the Ken Club in Boston with Pee Wee Russell and Max Kaminsky and Miff Mole. And they needed a Boston rhythm section... I was playing seven nights and Sunday afternoon for four or six weeks", "doc_title": "George Wein interviewed by Monk Rowe, New York City, New York, January 13, 2001", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/george-wein-interviewed-monk-rowe-new-york-city-new-york-january-13-2001"}, {"speaker": "Maxine Sullivan", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "the first group that I sang with at the Village Vanguard was a group made up of, it had Ralph Sutton on piano and Max Kaminsky on trumpet. It was Max Kaminsky's group.", "doc_title": "61529_Maxine Sullivan oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/61529/"}, {"speaker": "John Best", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "he told me who was in the band, he said Davy Tough, Max Kaminsky, Claude Thornhill and Sam Donahue... I was fortunate enough to get with that band", "doc_title": "John Best interviewed by Monk Rowe, San Diego, California, February 15, 1998", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/john-best-interviewed-monk-rowe-san-diego-california-february-15-1998"}, {"speaker": "Bud Freeman", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "Max Kaminsky was still going very strongly; and then Eddie on tuning what Eddie called the pork chop... and myself on tenor.", "doc_title": "66100_Bud Freeman oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/66100/"}, {"speaker": "Freddie Moore", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "Max Kaminsky and myself, we was working at clubs down in the Village... Just a trio, myself and Max Kaminsky and Art Hodes.", "doc_title": "67260_Freddie Moore oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/67260/"}]}